 2. PROGRAM TOTALS COMPARISON
================================================================================

 These are the raw "summary:" lines from each cachegrind output.

 Format: events: Ir Bc Bcm Bi Bim

 BEFORE:
   summary: 29,803,279,862  1,275,053,700  32,116,079  77,058,319  873,075

 AFTER:
   summary: 27,471,837,836    978,333,789  23,921,905  38,435,839  873,360

 DIFF (AFTER − BEFORE):
           -2,331,442,026   -296,719,911  -8,194,174 -38,622,480     +285

 Percentage change:
   Ir:   −7.82%    (2.33 billion fewer instructions)
   Bc:  −23.27%    (297 million fewer branches)
   Bcm: −25.51%    (8.2 million fewer mispredictions)
   Bi:  −50.12%    (38.6 million fewer indirect branches)
   Bim:  +0.03%    (negligible — noise)

 INTERPRETATION:
   The Ir reduction (−7.82%) is the primary performance metric.
   The Bc reduction (−23.27%) shows that the replaced library functions
   contained many internal branches (if/else in polynomial evaluation).
   The Bcm reduction (−25.51%) shows those branches were hard to predict.
   The Bi reduction (−50.12%) is dramatic — the glibc trig functions used
   many indirect calls (function pointer dispatch in the math library).
   After replacing them with inline code, indirect branches were halved.


